The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 L amp;T mum on Spectrum deal size

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, Feb. 3: Larsen amp; Toubro Ltd is buying out Spectrum Infotech Pvt. Ltd, a Bangalore-based aerospace and defence electronics research and development company, for an undisclosed sum. 

 The engineering and construction giant informed the stock exchanges today that it was acquiring 100 per cent share of Spectrum Infotech, a company that specialises in developing software and hardware for embedded computation, control and signal processing. 

 Spectrum is currently engaged in designing and developing prototype sub-systems and units.

 The acquisition is in line with L amp;Ts plan to strengthen its leadership position in the area of defence electronics and avionics. In Siemens fold, Spectrum Infotech will be managed by the companys newly launched Strategic Electronics Centre in Bangalore, which focuses on defence electronics, avionics, and aerospace solutions.

 The buyers of Spectrum software and hardware technologies and products include defence research and development laboratories, aeronautical development agency, combat vehicles development establishment, instrument research and development establishment, Naval Science amp; Technological Laboratory, Defence Bio-Engineering and Electro Medical Laboratory. 

 Apart from L amp;T, companies like Ashok Leyland have also been eyeing the defence business.

 L amp;T has posted robust third-quarter results on the back of a strong order flow in its core businesses. The company reported a robust 96 per cent increase in net profit, which propelled its share prices on the bourses to a high of Rs 2,382. On Friday, the L amp;T share price ended at Rs 2200.95.

 Led by a strong growth in the infrastructure and hydrocarbon sectors, L amp;Ts net profit zoomed to Rs 259.27 crore for the quarter ended December 31, 2005 from Rs 132.35 crore in the previous corresponding period. Gross sales registered an increase of 14 per cent at Rs 3,719 crore for the quarter versus Rs 3,267 crore in the same period a year ago. 

 The company bagged new orders worth Rs 7397 crore during the October-December quarter, reflecting a 108 per cent growth compared with the year-ago period. Its order book position for the first nine months of the fiscal stood at Rs 16,211 crore, a rise of 80 per cent over the last fiscal.

 Recently, L amp;T in consortium with Patel Engineering, has bagged a 520-mw hydro power project of Rs 439.07 crore from the National Hydroelectric Power Corporation Ltd. The project, Parbati Hydro Electric Project Stage (III), is located at Kullu in Himachal Pradesh and is expected to be completed in 56 months. 

 Earlier, L amp;T and Samsung Heavy Industries Co. Ltd. (SHI) of Korea jointly bagged a $456-million Vasai East Development Project from ONGC. 




